                     <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-258-victim2023 t18291029-258-viclabel1448"></join>, from her person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>ANN FREAK. I am a widow. On the 5th of October I was at the corner of <placeName id="t18291029-258-crimeloc1449">Monmouth-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18291029-258-crimeloc1449" type="placeName" value="Monmouth-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18291029-258-crimeloc1449" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-258-off1446 t18291029-258-crimeloc1449"></join>, between eight and nine o'clock in the evening, and felt my shawl taken off my shoulder - I said, "For God's sake, don't take my shawl;" I saw the prisoner near me: I saw no more of my shawl till I saw it at the Magistrate's the same evening - two officers came up, and assisted me.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Did you ask me to lead you out of the public-house? A. I am not saying contrary to that.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. She threw her shawl off when she was sitting on the step of a door, and was sick from the effects of the liquor - she told me to take care of it - I was holding her when the officer came up.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-258-person2024">
                  JOHN 
                  THURTELL
               <interp inst="t18291029-258-person2024" type="surname" value="THURTELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-258-person2024" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-258-person2024" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was on my beat that evening, and saw this old lady, who had had a drop, but was not incapable of taking care of herself; the prisoner was with her - she set her down, and then drew the shawl from off her back, and tucked it under her hams; I said to my serjeant,"Do you see that?" he said Yes; I went and asked the prisoner to assist me up with the old lady; she said she was not able; I got her up, and the prisoner took the shawl from her hams, and went away; my serjeant stopped her.</p>
               <p>PHILIP RILEY. I am serjeant of the Police. I saw the prisoner shifting the shawl under her - I said to her, "Why don't you assist the woman?" she said, "I am very bad, and can't;" she went away with the shawl, and I stopped her. She and another sat on the step - the old lady sat on the flag-stones; the prisoner had got as far as the public-house when I stopped her.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18291029-258-verdict1450" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18291029-258-verdict1450" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 24.</p>
